After you do those 3 things, send me the next build log if it still fails.

it say "build fail" with the message "Command "npm run build" exited with 127"

That error means:

npm run build is trying to run something that does not exist

In your case, the most likely cause is still this line in package.json:

"build": "tsc -b && vite build"

The 127 error usually means:

command not found

So Vercel is still likely trying to run tsc.

Do this exactly in GitHub
Step 1

Open your GitHub repo.

Step 2

Click on:

package.json
Step 3

Click the pencil/edit button.

Step 4

Find this section:

"scripts": {
  "dev": "vite",
  "build": "tsc -b && vite build",
  "preview": "vite preview"
}
Step 5

Replace it with this:

"scripts": {
  "dev": "vite",
  "build": "vite build",
  "preview": "vite preview"
}
Step 6

Scroll down and click:

Commit changes
Then add this file
Step 7

In GitHub, click:

Add file
Create new file
Step 8

Name it:

vercel.json
Step 9

Paste this in:

{
  "$schema": "https://openapi.vercel.sh/vercel.json",
  "installCommand": "npm install --include=dev --no-audit --no-fund",
  "buildCommand": "npm run build",
  "outputDirectory": "dist"
}
Step 10

Commit changes

Then check Vercel
Step 11

Go to Vercel → your project → Settings

Step 12

Find:

Node.js Version

Set it to:

20.x
Step 13

Save

Then redeploy
Step 14

Go to:

Deployments
Step 15

Click:

Redeploy
choose without cache if it shows that option
Very important check

After editing package.json, open it again in GitHub and confirm the build line now says exactly:

"build": "vite build"

If it still says:

"build": "tsc -b && vite build"

then the change did not save.

